---------------------------------------------------------------------------
- README file for barchetta reference application                          -
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

Description
-----------
This README is intended to explain the usage of barchetta reference
application. This reference application intends to show how to configure
Barchetta using BCM APIs. This application is tested with a specific test
setup and might not work on all environments.

It might require to modify the files in this folder for any customizations and
to see the desired outcome. Please feel free to consult the Broadcom AE's for
any assistance regarding this application.

Prerequisite
------------
Before using this reference application for a different test setup, it is
required to modify below details in the application:
1. USB device details:
    - Required to define the USB_DEV_SERIAL_CHIP0 with actual USB serial
      number used for the test in barchetta_common.h file. Running the
      reference application, lists all the USB serial numbers available on the
      system, choose the one applicable for the test setup.
2. MDIO bus address:
    - The PHY ID used in the application is the MDIO bus address used for the
      chip setup. Required to define PHY_ID0 with this detail in the
      barchetta_common.h file.
3. Chip ID:
    - Based on the package used for the test, the CHIP_ID0 define in the
      barchetta_common.h file required to be modified accordingly.
        For 81338, this has to be 0x1338
        For 81381, this has to be 0x1381
4. MDIO WRITE/READ API Trace Enable:
    - Enable "BCM_PLP_MDIO_TRACE_WRITE_ENABLE" compilation flag in "Makefile" to print
      the MDIO Write API data/address transactions.

      Ex: MDIO Write Trace is enabled in the Makefile
      ADD_FLAGS += -DBCM_PLP_MDIO_TRACE_WRITE_ENABLE

    - Enable "BCM_PLP_MDIO_TRACE_READ_ENABLE" compilation flag in "Makefile" to print
      the MDIO Read API data/address transactions.

      Ex: MDIO Read Trace is enabled in the Makefile
      ADD_FLAGS += -DBCM_PLP_MDIO_TRACE_READ_ENABLE
      
    - Enable "BCM_PLP_FORCE_TX_TRAINING_ENABLE" compilation flag in "Makefile" to enable
      enable force Tx training demonstration code. Otherwise, AN demonstration code will
      be executed.

	  Ex: Force Tx training is enabled in the Makefile
	  ADD_FLAGS += -DBCM_PLP_FORCE_TX_TRAINING_ENABLE

    - By default these options are disabled in the Makefile.
      Ex: MDIO Write/Read Trace, Force Tx Training is disabled.
      #ADD_FLAGS += -DBCM_PLP_MDIO_TRACE_WRITE_ENABLE
      #ADD_FLAGS += -DBCM_PLP_MDIO_TRACE_READ_ENABLE
      #ADD_FLAGS += -DBCM_PLP_FORCE_TX_TRAINING_ENABLE

      Note: INITIALIZE/MEMSET EVERY FUNCTION PARAMETERS TO zero,
      TO AVOID FUTURE COMPATIBILITY ISSUES WITH THE DRIVER.

In Linux, the VCP driver and D2XX driver are incompatible with each other.
When a FTDI device is plugged in, the VCP driver must be unloaded before a
D2XX application can be run. Use the remove module (rmmod) command to do
this:
  # sudo rmmod ftdi_sio
  # sudo rmmod usbserial
When the FTDI device is power cycled or reset the VCP driver will be reloaded.
The rmmod process must be repeated each time this occurs, before running the
D2XX application. Refer the FTDI driver documentation for more details.


Usage
-----
To build the reference application, use the following commands:
  # make clean
  # make

To run the sample application, use the binary image in the bin directory with
the sudo permission (if not root user), as follows:
  # sudo ./bin/barchetta_reference_app_25G_1x25G_NRZ

